<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-270-780  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 270 780.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  March 25 1990 v139 pF9(N) pF9(L) 25 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Truckers swap CB's for satellites. (Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Andrews, Edmund L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Trucking firms, and others - barge owners, small aircraftoperators and oil riggers - are installing satellite trackingsystems.andP;  Truckers use mobile satellite links to track and controltheir vehicles on the road.andP;  This technology involves atransmitter on a truck that sends hourly signals, which bounce offa satellite and down to a satellite company's headquarters; then,signals are passed on to a customer's headquarters by telephonecommunications.andP;  The cost of satellite communication has fallendramatically, with terminals now costing about $4,000.andP;  On boardsystems need only 25 to 40 watts to beam their signal.andP;  Theindustry supplying the satellite links is expected to grow rapidlyin the next few years.andP;  One analyst expects the industry to growfrom $100 million in 1989 to $6 billion in 1994, as the technologyspreads to other markets.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsTracking SystemsApplicationsTrucking Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Geostar 2.C system operation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>